        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-17T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="800" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d800">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/11–1745: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Lebanon</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mattison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-17T12:00:00+02:00">November 17, 1945—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 9:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>369. President Truman’s statement on Palestine and British Foreign Minister’s
                    statement in Parliament have been greeted with reserve, officials stating that
                    they need time to study proposals. It would seem that cautious attitude arises
                    from desire to await Arab League reaction. However, undercurrent of feeling is
                    against proposal to admit 1500 Jews monthly on the grounds this constitutes
                    violation of White Paper. Review of problem by impartial Anglo-American
                    Commission is not objected to, but any proposals for trusteeship are frowned
                    upon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mattison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
